    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It's a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/guide/language/generics.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">generics</a> literal. It means that you don't know the type of class this <code>Class</code> instance is representing, but you are still using the generic version.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>if you knew the class, you'd use <code>Class&lt;Foo&gt;</code>. That way you can create a new instance, for example, without casting: <code>Foo foo = clazz.newInstance();</code></li>\n<li>if you don't use generics at all, you'll get a warning at least (and not using generics is generally discouraged as it may lead to hard-to-detect side effects)</li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 230303,
      "reputation" : 14598,
