    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>Class</code> is a parameterizable class, hence you can use the syntax <code>Class&lt;T&gt;</code> where <code>T</code> is a type. By writing <code>Class&lt;?&gt;</code>, you're declaring a <code>Class</code> object which can be of any type (<code>?</code> is a wildcard). The <code>Class</code> type is a type that contains meta-information about a class. </p>\n\n<p>It's always good practice to refer to a generic type by specifying his specific type, by using <code>Class&lt;?&gt;</code> you're respecting this practice (you're aware of <code>Class</code> to be parameterizable) but you're not restricting your parameter to have a specific type.</p>\n\n<p>Reference about Generics and Wildcards: <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/wildcards.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/wildcards.html</a></p>\n\n<p>Reference about <code>Class</code> object and reflection (the feature of Java language used to introspect itself): <a href=\"https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/articles/java/javareflection-1536171.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/articles/java/javareflection-1536171.html</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 406375,
      "reputation" : 5102,
      "user_id" : 775849,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5201305715ba4d8d60df41e6bc107146?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Jasonw",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/775849/jasonw"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1333009817,
    "creation_date" : 1333009817,
    "answer_id" : 9921749,
    "question_id" : 9921676,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In generics, an unknown type is represented by the wildcard character \"?\". Read <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/wildcards.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a> for official example.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 36858,
      "reputation" : 114943,
      "user_id" : 105224,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 73,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1dc604233d8a0c48f0884769acb1fb93?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Andreas Dolk",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/105224/andreas-dolk"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 103,
    "last_activity_date" : 1333011342,
    "creation_date" : 1333011342,
    "answer_id" : 9922089,
    "question_id" : 9921676,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>This <code>&lt;?&gt;</code> is a beast. It often leads to confusion and errors, because, when you see it first, then you start believing, <code>&lt;?&gt;</code> is a wildcard for <em>any java type</em>. Which is .. not true. <code>&lt;?&gt;</code> is <strong>the unknown type</strong>, a slight and nasty difference.</p>\n\n<p>It's not a problem when you use it with <code>Class</code>. Both lines work and compile:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Class anyType = String.class;\nClass &lt;?&gt; theUnknownType = String.class;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>But</strong> - if we start using it with collections, then we see strange compiletime errors:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;?&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;Object&gt;();  // ArrayList&lt;?&gt; is not allowed\nlist.add(\"a String\");                    // doesn't compile ...\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Our <code>List&lt;?&gt;</code> is not a collection, that is suitable for just any type of object. It can only store one type: the mystic \"unkown type\". Which is not a real type, for sure.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5677475,
      "reputation" : 1368,
      "user_id" : 4490081,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 75,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1eea7948aafac7de81d4f198732d985f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "SRaj",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4490081/sraj"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1609573002,
    "last_edit_date" : 1609573002,
    "creation_date" : 1609571923,
    "answer_id" : 65536846,
    "question_id" : 9921676,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>It means, the Class reference type can hold any Class object which represents any type. If JVM loads a type, a class object representing that type will be present in JVM. we can get the metadata regarding the type from that class object which is used very much in reflection package.</p>\n<p>Suppose you have a a class named &quot;myPackage.MyClass&quot;. Assuming that is in classpath, the following statements are equivalent.</p>\n<pre><code>Class&lt;?&gt; myClassObject = MyClass.class; //compile time check\n\nClass&lt;?&gt; myClassObject = Class.forname(&quot;myPackage.MyClass&quot;); //only runtime check\n</code></pre>\n<p>This works in a similar fashion if the Class&lt;?&gt; reference is in method argument as well.</p>\n<p>Please note that the class &quot;Class&quot; does not have a public constructor. So you cannot instantiate &quot;Class&quot; instances with &quot;new&quot; operator.</p>\n"
  } ],
